        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 51-year-old male who presents to the outpatient clinic with a chief complaint of widespread muscle aching and stiffness that has been progressively worsening over the past three weeks. He appears mildly fatigued but is alert and oriented, dressed casually in work clothes. He is of average build with a slightly increased waist circumference, reflecting a sedentary desk job lifestyle. He reports the pain is diffuse, affecting primarily his lower back, thighs, and upper arms, with a dull, aching quality rated 6/10 on the pain scale. The discomfort is worse in the mornings and after prolonged sitting, and is only partially relieved by over-the-counter analgesics.\n\n{patientName} works as a mid-level manager at a logistics company, spending 8–10 hours a day at a desk. He commutes 45 minutes each way and describes his job as highly stressful, with frequent deadlines and staff management responsibilities. He lives with his wife and two teenage children in a suburban home. He considers himself socially active, enjoying weekend barbecues with neighbors and occasional fishing trips, though physical activity has decreased significantly over the past year.\n\nHis diet consists largely of processed convenience foods and takeout, with limited fruits and vegetables. He drinks 3–4 cups of coffee daily and consumes alcohol socially (approximately 6–8 standard drinks per week). He is a former smoker who quit 7 years ago after a 15 pack-year history. He does not engage in regular exercise and reports poor sleep quality with frequent awakenings, attributing it to work stress. He denies fever, rash, joint swelling, or neurological symptoms."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9abffcb2-ed59-44cf-946c-e99ea59641d9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a known history of dyslipidemia, diagnosed approximately 4 years ago and managed with a statin. He was diagnosed with hypertension two years ago, currently controlled on antihypertensive therapy. He has a history of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD), managed intermittently with proton pump inhibitors. He has no prior hospitalizations and no history of surgery. He reports no known autoimmune, endocrine, or neuromuscular conditions. His BMI is approximately 27.8 kg/m². He does not use recreational drugs. Vaccination history is up to date, including influenza and COVID-19 boosters. {patientName} reports his muscle symptoms began approximately three weeks ago following a period of increased work stress and after a weekend of unaccustomed physical labor (helping a friend move house). He has not seen a specialist previously for this complaint."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
